    <definition xml:id="def-informed-decision">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Informed decision-making is the process of using data and evidence to make choices that are based on facts and analysis rather than assumptions or guesses.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <insight>
        <p>
             How to make informed decisions based on data:
            <ol>
                <li>Identify the problem or question to be addressed.</li>
                <li>Collect relevant data through surveys, experiments, or observations.</li>
                <li>Organize the data into useful forms such as frequency tables (both grouped and ungrouped).</li>
                <li>Represent the data visually using tables, histograms, and frequency polygons to identify patterns, trends, and relationships.</li>
                <li>Interpret the data to draw conclusions.</li>
                <li>Make informed decisions based on the analysis and interpretation of the data.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </insight>
